Theme of the assignment: Let’s practice visualization using base R and create cool maps. Load in the Cars93 dataset by running the following code chunk:

library(MASS)
data(Cars93)

The library function will load and attach add-on packages that have been previously installed on your machine. This will give you access to the functions and datasets available in the package. In general, you only need to install a package once (although it may require updating from time to time) but you need to access it using the library command every time you start a new session in R (and want the functionality).

The questions below use the Cars93 data frame as a source of data. This data frame is part of the MASS package and becomes available after loading it. You can get a view of the top of the data frame by using the head command. For more information, type ?Cars93. Let’s load Cars93 in,

Base R

Task 1

  1. Create a Frequency table and Relative Frequency table (latter uses percentages) for the variable Type. Make sure to round all digits to 3 digits.
frequency_table <- table(Cars93$Type)
print(frequency_table) 
## 
## Compact   Large Midsize   Small  Sporty     Van 
##      16      11      22      21      14       9
relative_frequency_table <- prop.table(table(Cars93$Type)) * 100
rounded_relative_table <- round(relative_frequency_table, 3)
print(rounded_relative_table)
## 
## Compact   Large Midsize   Small  Sporty     Van 
##  17.204  11.828  23.656  22.581  15.054   9.677
  1. Create a frequency bar graph for the variable Type. You can have count on the y axis.
frequency_table <- table(Cars93$Type)
barplot(frequency_table, ylab = "Count", xlab = "Type", main = "Frequency Bar Graph for varible Type")

  • Your axes should be labeled and legible
  • The bars should be of different colors
  • The plot should include a title using the main argument
  • The names, labels, and axes sizes (cex parameter) should be set to 1.2
  1. Create a pie chart of the variable Type.
frequency_table <- table(Cars93$Type)
pie(frequency_table,labels = names(frequency_table), cex = 1.2, main = "Pie Chart of the Types of Cars")

  • The plot should include a title using the main argument.
  • The names, labels, and axes sizes (cex parameter) should be set to 1.2
  1. What is the mode of the variable Type? Comment. Answer: Midsized cars are the most frequent in the bar graph there for is the mode

Task 2

  1. Create a histogram of the variable Horsepower.
hist(Cars93$Horsepower,main = "Histogram of Horsepower of The Cars",xlab="Horsepower",border="blue", col= "red", cex=1.2, xlim=c(min(Cars93$Horsepower), max(Cars93$Horsepower)))

  • Your axes should be labeled
  • The hist body should have a color (your choice, not too dark to obscure lines)
  • The plot should include a title using the main argument
  • The names, labels, and axes sizes should be set to 1.2
  1. Create a second histogram with breaks at 25 HP increments instead of 50.
hist(Cars93$Horsepower,breaks = seq(0,max(Cars93$Horsepower) + 25, by = 25), main = "Histogram of Horsepower of The Cars",xlab="Horsepower",border="blue", col= "red", cex=1.2, xlim=c(min(Cars93$Horsepower), max(Cars93$Horsepower)))

  • Use the breaks argument to define the classes
  • Other setting should be as in part (a)
  1. Which histogram more closely follows or rule of thumb for the suggested number of classes? Explain. Answer: The second histrogram because it is more spread out and shows the distribution of the data better because in the first histogram the data is pushed together and not as spead out.

Task 3

  1. What is the type of variable Passengers? (Categorical nominal/ordinal or Numerical discrete/continuous?) What happens if we were to make a histogram for Passengers? What is the problem with this graph? Answer: The varible Passengers is a numerical discrete varible. When you create a histogram as you see below, the graph is suggesting the data is continous when it is not.
hist(Cars93$Passengers,main = "Histogram of Passengers in The Cars",xlab="Passengers",border="blue", col= "red", cex=1.2, xlim=c(min(Cars93$Passengers), max(Cars93$Passengers)))

  1. Correct the problem in part (a) by creating a more appropriate visualization. Make sure to label your axes, place a title, choose a custom color as in the previous graphs. (Bonus: use factor() with levels option to display x axis values with no observations on the plot.)
passenger_frequency<- table(Cars93$Passengers)
barplot(passenger_frequency, main = "Bar Chart of Passengers", xlab= "Number of Passengers", ylab="Frequency", col="lightblue", border= "black")

Task 4

  1. Make a histogram of the variable Length (the default breaks are fine). Other aspects of the plot should be as in part (a) in Task 2.
hist(Cars93$Length,main = "Histogram of Length of The Cars",xlab="Length",border="blue", col= "red", cex=1.2, xlim=c(min(Cars93$Length), max(Cars93$Length)))

  1. What is the shape of the distribution? Answer: Skewed to the left because most of the data is on the right and all of the smaller values are on the right
